{"id":"1302.2572","submitter":"J. Zheng-Johansson X.","authors":"J.X. Zheng-Johansson","title":"Inference of the Universal Constancy of Planck Constant based on First\n  Principles","comments":"Presentation at the International Workshop DICE, Castiglioncello\n  (Tuscany), Italy, Sept, 2012","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Since its discovery by Max Planck in 1900, the Planck constant $h$ has been\ndemonstrated to be an universal constant, and its numerical value has been\naccurately determined based on experiments. Up to the present however the\nphysical origin of this fundamental constant has not been well understood, and\nthe numerical value of it has not been {\\it ab initio} predicted. $h$ is\ncharacteristic in two respects: 1) it is a universal constant with respect to\nall (quasi-) stationary dynamical processes of all matter particles and\nradiation fields, and 2) it has a specific numerical value. A theoretical\ninference of $h$, and a corresponding accounting for the physical origin of\n$h$, therefore needs be achieved in both respects. This paper presents a\ntheoretical exploration in the first respect, a mathematical inference of the\nuniversal constancy of $h$, based on the second law of thermodynamics, the\nprinciple of least action and the probability theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Jan 2013 10:50:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-02-12"}
